                    <item>
              <title>MON: Making the Transition to E-portfolios (Helen Dixon)</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/11505</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/11505</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Theme: Implementation&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Format: Activity/workshop&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Building up a portfolio of evidence is an established assessment process for a range of qualifications and is particularly suited to many vocational&nbsp;subjects&nbsp;where it is necessary to demonstrate skills and competencies&nbsp;(Wagner, 1998).&nbsp; Traditionally, portfolios have been paper-based, with folders of handwritten and printed evidence being collated for assessment and verification by awarding bodies.&nbsp; However, over the past ten years, many qualification providers have adopted the use of electronic or e-portfolios, enabling computer-based collation and&nbsp;assessment&nbsp;of evidence&nbsp;(Beetham, 2005).&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">The&nbsp;digitisation of portfolios has&nbsp;allowed them to be more accessible&nbsp;(Ball <em>et&nbsp;al</em>, 2010),&nbsp;efficient and flexible&nbsp;(Jisc, 2012), however, the successful implementation of an e-portfolio system requires a significant transformation in how evidence is documented and the assessment process is managed.&nbsp; An initial survey&nbsp;of tutors in a Further Education college&nbsp;as part of this study&nbsp;highlighted that comprehensive training in the use of e-portfolios is required&nbsp;in order to ensure the acceptance of the technology by&nbsp;educators.&nbsp; Furthermore, a need for&nbsp;tutors&nbsp;and learners to rethink the types of evidence presented for accreditation is required if qualification providers are&nbsp;to fully realise the potential benefits of e-portfolios and avoid situations where paper-based evidence is scanned and uploaded to the system, thereby creating additional work for tutors and learners.&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">In order to address these issues, a blended&nbsp;learning workshop&nbsp;has been developed for educators to assist them in making the transition to e-portfolios.&nbsp; The objectives of the workshop are to help educators to:&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="SCXW67448036">
<ul class="BulletListStyle1 SCXW67448036">
<li class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-listid="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Rethink how evidence is created and collated;&nbsp;</p>
</li>
<li class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="2" data-listid="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Find out how they can use an e-portfolio system to manage the assessment process;&nbsp;</p>
</li>
<li class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="3" data-listid="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Identify ways they can support students in developing the digital skills required to take ownership of their learning.&nbsp;</p>
</li>
</ul>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">The workshop template is platform-generic, allowing it to be customised to the needs of different subject areas and supplemented with additional training resources related to specific e-portfolio systems.&nbsp; While e-portfolios can be used in a variety of ways, the workshop focuses on their use for assessment and will assume that participants are already familiar with the use of traditional portfolios for evidence-based assessment.&nbsp; Workshop resources are hosted on a&nbsp;MoodleCloud&nbsp;site, allowing open access to them.&nbsp; All resources are shared under a Creative Commons Attribution&nbsp;ShareAlike&nbsp;(CC BY-SA) licence in alignment with the 'open' ethos of the conference.&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW67448036">
<p class="Paragraph SCXW67448036">Keywords: e-portfolios, assessment, vocational education, professional development, open educational resources, blended learning&nbsp;</p>
</div>
</div>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 17 Jan 2018 18:17:55 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>SAT: Break Out of the Box! How you can use xAPI to free in-house staff development (Katherine Hinchey)</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/11472</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/11472</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>You learn by doing and collaborating, watching videos, accessing just-in-time information from your mobile device, mentoring, and more. Why, then, does the Human Resources department only give you slides to learn from?</p>
<p>Today&rsquo;s workers and corporations are united in wanting more access to the formal, non-formal, and informal learning needed to support an increasingly skilled workforce (The Education Commission, 2016; Pew Research Center, 2016a and 2016b). However, today&rsquo;s corporations largely store their learning resources in virtual learning environments (VLEs) that have adopted a uniform way of storing content. This uniform way, called SCORM, was incredibly helpful when it was designed nineteen years ago, and it still has an important role to play today. When SCORM was created, computer-based training was relatively new and organisations needed a single way to store and track training. For a time, innovation in elearning stopped at the known, established boundaries of the VLE (Weller, 2014, p. 194).</p>
<p>Now, a new need has developed: a way to store and track learning when it occurs on mobile devices, or through social and collaborative activities, or offline by reading a book or engaging in stretch assignments, or when participating in simulations or augmented and virtual reality programmes.</p>
<p>An innovation that meets that need was first released in 2013, and had its last planned update in 2016. It is the Experience API (xAPI). xAPI provides a common format for capturing data from today&rsquo;s distributed learning landscape (Rustici Software, n.d.). With xAPI in place, you can free staff development from the confines of SCORM:</p>
<ul>
<li>Rely less on elearning courses designed from slides and more on learning experiences;</li>
<li>Recognise learning from formal and informal or non-formal activities (Downes, 2015);</li>
<li>And track not only clicks and views but also correlate learning with performance (Torrance, 2016).</li>
</ul>
<p>Managers and other decision-makers within learning departments and organisations are at a critical point. They need a source from which to gain a high-level, jargon-free understanding of the benefits of xAPI, common applications and uses of xAPI to support learners as they access modern and innovative learning opportunities, best practices and lessons learned, and information they should provide to their learning development and learning technology teams to prepare for implementation of xAPI (HT2 Labs, n.d.).</p>
<p>In my conference presentation, I will discuss and share a workshop created to meet those needs. The workshop helps managers, even those without extensive technical backgrounds, to be prepared to move forward with discussions and decisions about xAPI within their organisation. My presentation will show some of the workshop features and provide attendees with tools they can take with them, for use in their future endeavours.</p>
<h3>References</h3>
<p>Downes, A. (2015) '9 Practical Applications of Tin Can API', webinar presented by Rustici Software. 31 March. Available at <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/RusticiSoftware/ nine-applications-of-the-tin-can-api-xapi">https://www.slideshare.net/RusticiSoftware/</a><br /><a href="https://www.slideshare.net/RusticiSoftware/ nine-applications-of-the-tin-can-api-xapi">nine-applications-of-the-tin-can-api-xapi</a> (Accessed 1 November 2017).</p>
<p>The Education Commission (aka the International Commission on Financing Global Education Opportunity) (2016) <em>The Learning Generation: Investing in education for a changing world</em> [Online]. Available at <a href="http://report.educationcommission.org/downloads/">http://report.educationcommission.org/downloads/</a> (Accessed 18 November 2017).</p>
<p>HT2 Labs (n.d.) <em>The Learning Technology Manager's Guide to xAPI</em> [Online]. Available at <a href="https://www.ht2labs.com/resources/the-learning-technology-managers-guide-to-the-xapi/">https://www.ht2labs.com/resources/the-learning-technology-managers-guide-to-the-xapi/</a> (Accessed 9 December 2017).</p>
<p>Pew Research Center (2016a) <em>Lifelong Learning and Technology</em> [Online]. Available at <a href="http://www.pewinternet.org/2016/03/22/lifelong-learning-and-technology/">http://www.pewinternet.org/2016/03/22/lifelong-learning-and-technology/</a> (Accessed 18 November 2017).</p>
<p>Pew Research Center (2016b) <em>The State of American Jobs: How the shifting economic landscape is reshaping work and society and affecting the way people think about the skills and training they need to get ahead</em> [Online]. Available at <a href="http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/2016/10/06/the-state-of-american-jobs/">http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/2016/10/06/the-state-of-american-jobs/</a> (Accessed 18 November 2017).</p>
<p>Rustici Software (n.d.) <em>Experience API</em> [Online]. Available at <a href="https://experienceapi.com/">https://experienceapi.com/</a> (Accessed 1 November 2017).</p>
<p>Torrance, M. (2016) 'The xAPI: What Does an Instructional Designer Need to Know?', presentation given at <em>Learning Solutions Conference &amp; Expo.</em> Orlando, Florida, 16-18 March. Available at <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/torrancelearning/xapi-what-does-an-instructional-designer-need-to-know">https://www.slideshare.net/torrancelearning/xapi-what-does-an-instructional-designer-need-to-know</a> (Accessed 1 November 2017).</p>
<p>Weller, M. (2014) <em>The Battle for Open: How openness won and why it doesn't feel like victory</em>, London, ubiquity press. Available at <a href="http://www.ubiquitypress.com/ site/books/detail/11/battle-for-open/">http://www.ubiquitypress.com/</a><br /><a href="http://www.ubiquitypress.com/ site/books/detail/11/battle-for-open/">site/books/detail/11/battle-for-open/</a> (Accessed 2 May 2016).</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 05 Jan 2018 05:53:35 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Vicky Hindle&#39;s Design Narrative: Using Google Classrooms to support learners in and outside of the classroom.</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/9869</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/9869</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>I am an Access to HE Coordinator and tutor, working for a large FE College within Yorkshire and Humber region. The aim of Access to HE is to prepare 19+ adult learners University level study I coordinate two pathways at one of the smaller campuses - Humanities and Social Sciences and Health Science Professions. I also teach Psychology, Sociology, Social Policy and Study Skills. My role as a coordinator involves curriculum design and setting up and moderating VLEs such as Moodle and Google Classrooms. &nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Situation</strong></p>
<p>The College has recently adopted a new VLE platform - Google Classrooms. The College has also loaned out Chromebooks to students, so&nbsp; I set up Google Classrooms in order to support students in and outside of the classroom.&nbsp; The Chromebooks have been useful in that I have been able to set up online interactive tasks, such as quizzes, that students can do in the classroom or at home. Students are also able to open up shared documents within the Google Classroom and collaborate on them.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The Technology Enhanced Learning Team (TEL) were the key actors in setting up and facilitating training on the Google platform, as where the teachers who used Google Classrooms. The TEL team adopted Google Classrooms in the belief that...</p>
<ul type="disc">
<li>It is easier to use than Moodle (which it is. However, it is worth noting that there are some things that Moodle can do that Google Classrooms can't do - see 'Actions below').</li>
<li>It is easier to communicate with students.</li>
<li>It is easy to upload and use&nbsp; a variety of learning materials including Word Docs, presentations, YouTube videos etc.</li>
<li>It is easier for students and tutor's to collaborate online -&nbsp; tutors can post shared docs and presentations for the students to collaborate on.</li>
<li>It will cut down on the cost of printed materials.</li>
<li>It will promote independent learning.</li>
<li>It is available across different platforms (google and android apps), so students and tutors can access Google classrooms on their mobile devices as well as desktop computers.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;<strong style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Task</strong></p>
<p>I set up Google classrooms in order to achieve the points highlighted above, in the 'Situation' section. However, I was particular interested in developing&nbsp; real world I.T. Skills, which will stand students in good stead in both the work place and at University.</p>
<p>&nbsp;I also wanted to ensure that all learners have access to the learning materials used in each lesson at all times. This is particularly important for adult learners, many of whom have&nbsp; work and family commitments outside of college. If a student can't make it to lesson for childcare or work reasons, then they can catch up on lessons missed on Google Classrooms. I also wanted to encourage more collaboration and discussion in and outside of the classroom, particularly among the quieter groups. The measure of success for this was how many students contributed to a discussion in and outside of class (see actions and results for more details on this.)</p>
<p>&nbsp;In addition to this, I also hoped that the use of Google Classrooms would improve retention, attendance and achievement. Compared to last year, retention is better for both of the pathways I teach on. Though attendance is low for one group.&nbsp; It is difficult to comment on achievement rates at this time whilst students are still on the course, though I have noticed that more low attenders&nbsp; are still passing their assignments at merit level compared to previous years. Could this be a sign that these students are making full use of Google Classrooms. Whilst this is anecdotal evidence, research by L&oacute;pez-P&eacute;rez et al (2011) suggests that blended and online learning can improve retention and achievement.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Action and results&nbsp;</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li value="1">Last year, using the credentials provided to me by the College, I set up Google Classroom account for teachers.</li>
<li>Once I had set up classrooms for each Access to HE unit, I invited students to join each classroom using a unique code. However, not all students joined the classroom. At the start of this academic year, I made sure that students had joined all classes during the induction week. Tutors can give students access to Google classrooms themselves, though this may be time consuming for large Cohorts.</li>
</ol><ol type="1">
<li value="3">I then used Google Classrooms to share documents with the students and upload lesson materials. I tend to make announcements in the stream, but upload lesson material to the &lsquo;About&rsquo; section as I can organise the materials week by week. As mentioned above, this seems to have been beneficial for low attenders as they are still achieving despite their low attendance. This may indicate that they are engaging with Google Classrooms outside of the classrooms.</li>
<li>I have also created quizzes using Socrates, Google forms and Moodle Cloud and posted links to these on Google Classrooms. For quizzes, I settled on Moodle Cloud. Whilst Socrates is good, students have to input a separate password to access the quiz. Whereas with the quizzes on Moodle Cloud, students just log in using the same credentials to log into Google Classrooms. This has help to engage all students in the classroom as they tell me they enjoy taking part in the quizzes. It is also useful for me, as I can check their understanding of the topic.</li>
<li>In addition to this, I have posted links to Padlet on google classrooms, so that students can share ideas from discussion activities. For example, when discussing the strengths and limitations of a particular theory. &nbsp;</li>
<li>Within the classroom environment, all students contribute well to the Padlet activities. However, they do not seem to engage as well with this activity outside of the classroom. To overcome this problem, I plan to set an activity linked to one of the unit criteria. So, in order to pass the unit, they will have to complete the activity online.</li>
<li>This year, I started&nbsp; sharing documents such as google slides or docs on Google Classrooms, which students can work on together. This has also helped to engage all students. For example, each student within a group can work on a particular slide. Furthermore, once the students have completed their presentation, it will always be available on Google Classrooms. This is particularly useful for students who have missed lessons. However, some students might complain that these students have not contributed to the presentation. To overcome this problem, students who have missed a lesson, could create a presentation and post it to the classroom. To encourage this, I could mark the student as attending a lesson (e.g. A virtual attendance mark, which contributes to their overall attendance rate).</li>
<li>One of the limitations of Google Classrooms, is that I can&rsquo;t create a Turnitin assignment, unlike moodle. So I post links on Google classrooms to Turnitin assignments on the Moodle Cloud. Students can sign into Moodle Cloud using their student account for Google, so they don&rsquo;t have to use a separate password. Turnitin is a plagiarism checker, which students will also have to use a university. I also do all of my marking on Turnitin, so students always have access to feedback online.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;R<strong style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->eflections</strong></p>
<p>I enjoy using Google Classrooms, and students have told me they find it useful, particularly when they have missed lessons. However, Google Classrooms is a cloud based platform which assumes that all students will have access to a computer and the internet at home. However, I do have some students who do not have access to the internet. So, even though the have been loaned a Chromebook, they may not be able to use it at home without internet access (as Chromebooks are a cloud based device). To overcome this problem, perhaps the College could loan out dongles to those who need it, though I appreciate that this will cost money.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>As I have already mentioned, students are engaging well with the Chromebooks and Google Classrooms within the Classroom environment. Low attenders seem to be engaging with this platform outside of the classroom as the are still passing their assignments. Furthermore, one of my groups is quiet and can be difficult to engage in group discussions, but I have used Google Classrooms to overcome this problem. I now get students to discuss their ideas in small groups and then post something to the Padlet or Google Docs. Once they have done this activity, I will then get each group to share their ideas with the rest of the class. The act of getting them to write down their ideas first seems to have helped the students engage more with discussion activities. However, this is only one cohort, so it is not possible to generalise the results.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Whilst Google Classrooms seems to work well within a classroom context, I need to use it more effectively to encourage collaboration outside of the classroom. Even when I have set up tasks outside of the classroom, not all students have engaged with these tasks. In order to overcome this problem, for the next academic year, I plan to link one or more of the unit criteria to the online tasks, which they will have to complete in order to pass the unit. For example, contributing to a online discussion, just as Open University students do.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Nevertheless, Google Classrooms was met with some resistance when it was first set up. As I a result of this, I found that I was the only tutor using it.&nbsp; Students ended up having to look for lessons materials on both Google Classrooms and Moodle, which caused some confusion. &nbsp;Perhaps this was the result of the&nbsp; work that needed to be done to either transfer existing materials from Moodle to Google Classrooms or to develop new materials.&nbsp; There are also some things that Moodle can do that&nbsp; Google Classrooms cannot do. For example, you cannot upload Turnitin assignments to Google classrooms. In order to overcome this problem, I have started using Moodle Cloud. This enables me to&nbsp; post links to Moodle Cloud from Google Classrooms; for example, a link to a Turntin assignment and students will not need a separate password or username to access this. In addition to this, materials for 'old' Moodle, can be transferred to the new online Moodle Cloud if necessary. As a result of this, and more training offered by the College, more tutors are engaging with the Google Platform.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>References:&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p lang="en-US">L&oacute;pez-P&eacute;rez, V., P&eacute;rez-L&oacute;pez, C., Rodr&iacute;guez-Ariza, L. (2011) &lsquo;Blended learning in higher education: Students&rsquo; perceptions and their relation to outcomes&rsquo;, Computers &amp; Education, vol. 56, no3, pp. 818-826 [Online]. Available at&nbsp; <a href="http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360131510003088">http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360131510003088</a> (Accessed 20th of March 2016)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Resources</p>
<p>Google Classrooms: <a href="https://support.google.com/edu/classroom/answer/6020279?hl=en">https://support.google.com/edu/classroom/answer/6020279?hl=en</a></p>
<p>Padlet <a href="https://padlet.com/">https://padlet.com/</a></p>
<p>Turnitin: <a href="http://www.turnitinuk.com/">http://www.turnitinuk.com/</a></p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 06 Apr 2016 13:27:08 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>David Appel’s design narrative: Developing blended learning elements which facilitate group work and peer-feedback</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8963</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8963</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<h2 dir="ltr">Narrator</h2>
<p dir="ltr">My role was to support a teacher in conceptualising, designing, development and implementation of an online learning activity.</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">Situation</h2>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">University of Applied Sciences, Department for Social Work</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Compulsory elective subject in a bachelor curriculum for Social Work.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Students (approx. 40) attending the course into their 3rd or 4th term, having completed several courses covering theoretical and methodical basics of the field.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Students have to deliver a report on a project they have worked on during the course. This is a group work of 3-4 students and delivered at the end of the term.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Previously, a significant proportion of the face-to-face course time has been used for organizing group work, providing instruction and facilitating communication. Peer feedback in the face-to-face environment has proven to be very time-consuming and has often not been leading to satisfactory results</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">LMS: Moodle (Students have worked with Moodle before, but are not necessarily experienced with collaborative elements and practices; teacher is fairly familiar with Moodle)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 dir="ltr">Task</h2>
<p dir="ltr">I have focused on opportunities to improve efficiency and effectiveness of group collaboration in this course. I decided to use blended learning elements which would allow to guide students towards group work and communication in a virtual environment. I selected administrative, organizational and methodological elements of writing a term paper which could be supported by with online components. The measure of success was a reduction of administrative and organisational efforts by the teacher and administrative staff.</p>
<p dir="ltr">I also included elements of reflection and evaluation for the students to &nbsp;take an active, participative, and critical role (providing peer-feedback at several stages of the paper writing process). The success factor was a consistent quality in the term papers delivered, not below the quality of previous papers delivered in the standard course format.</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">Actions</h2>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Together with the teacher in charge I drafted a concept for the course, including goals, key stakeholders, format and sequence of elements included, implementation of a pilot, implementation of the final course, and evaluation by students, teacher, and supportive staff. The result was a common understanding of the goals as well as the actions to be taken and related responsibilities.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">I then developed the main elements and run a pilot with a few selected testers not yet involved in the course design. It turned out that several elements were not sufficiently described or did not work exactly the way they were intended.</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">On the basis of the pilot we adapted the course design were necessary and then run the course for an entire term. At the end of the turn we evaluated the results, questioned students, staff and teacher and analysed the overall outcomes.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 dir="ltr">Results</h2>
<p dir="ltr">The papers delivered were of a consistent quality at about the same level as in the previous version of the course (without blended learning elements). The effort for preparing and developing the course was significant, during the course support and occasional adjustments were necessary which also meant some additional effort for both teacher and supportive staff. However, most of the issues could be resolved for the next term and without the one-time preparational efforts qualitative as well as quantitative objectives could be met.</p>
<p dir="ltr">A survey conducted among the students showed that most of them appreciated the design of the course, but would have liked to use the space for further collaboration more extensively.</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">Reflections</h2>
<p dir="ltr">It is important to create a detailed design of the course - including goals, key stakeholders, elements and sequencing, evaluation, etc. - in order to make sure that all involved parties have the same understanding of the project. However, even with a detailed design there are issues which cannot be anticipated and therefore running a pilot with people who have not been involved previously is crucial to discover any gaps and flaws. At the end, an evaluation can reveal further gaps and issues, but also provide input for further development.</p>
<p dir="ltr">&nbsp;</p>
<h3>CompendiumLD Map</h3>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a title="Peer-feedback on term paper concept2 by David Appel, on Flickr" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/131689978@N02/17016406390"><img src="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5449/17016406390_896948cd86_b.jpg" alt="Peer-feedback on term paper concept2" width="650" height="728" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
