          <pubDate>Tue, 06 Apr 2010 14:25:15 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>The Ethics of Mobile Learning</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3142</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3142</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>One of the striking things to come out of the MOTILL Project was the apparent lack of any coherent ethical guidance with respect to the use of mobile devices for teaching and learning.&nbsp; The practicioners I interviewed all brought this up as an area where guidance is crucially needed.</p>
<p>Much of the existing work that has been done in this area concerns research ethics and the ways in which one might research mobile learning in an ethical way.&nbsp; This is certainly something that I'm interested in, but it seems more innovative to me to expand the boundaries of the investigation beyond teaching and learning to look at the impact of communications technologies on social interaction more generally construed, on (inter-)subjectivity, and on processes of norm-formation and social mores.</p>
<p>I apreciate that this might take the project somewhat outside of the IET purview.&nbsp; The challenge of understanding the wider ethical ramifications of modern technologies is undoubtedly one which educational technologists should address.</p>
<p>I have two lines of inquiry in mind at the moment.&nbsp; Firstly, and drawing on my PhD research, would be a more general account of the relationship between technology and autonomy arising from the Frankfurt School tradition in critical theory.&nbsp; This will provide an initial framework for showing where some of the ethical considerations specific to mobile technologes might arise, and also has the virtue of allowing me to draw parallels and other links with pedagogies which emphasize the autonomy of the learner.&nbsp; I am also interested in drawing on Heidegger's later philosophy of technology to flesh out the kind of philosophical worries associated with the advance of technologies.</p>
<p>Obvioulsy, this might seem a little philosophy heavy for TEL, and I am keen to be quite explicit about the link to teaching and learning.</p>
<p>One realistic output might be a 'tool-kit' for practitioners with a bit of ethical guidance and ten principles to think about.&nbsp; It might even be worth looking up the relevant legislation and sticking that in there too!</p>
<p>I welcome any thoughts or reflections you may have to offer.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 15 Mar 2010 12:46:23 +0000</pubDate>
